'''André Ungar''' (born 1928) [[Hungary|Hungarian]]-born doctor of [[philosophy]], [[Liturgy|liturgist]], [[Activism|social activist]], and [[rabbi]] who has lived in [[England]], [[South Africa]] and the [[United States]]. In 1956, South Africa ordered him to leave on account of his decrying of [[apartheid]]. Rabbi Ungar is the author of ''Living Judaism'' (Reform Synagogue of Great Britain: 1958), and ''Judaism for Our Time'' (RSGB: 1973); and various articles on the subject of [[Jewish philosophy]]. His alternative, poetic translations of the [[Amidah]] have appeared in all editions and versions of [[Siddur Sim Shalom]], of the Conservative Jewish denomination.<ref>{{cite news|title=Article on Expulsion from South Africa|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/vieilles_annonces/8278381884/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=CITY RABBI ORDERED TO LEAVE THE COUNTRY |url=http://www.sajewishreport.co.za/pdf/2009/oct/2-october-2009.pdf }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=About Temple Emanuel of the Pascack Valley |url=http://tepv.org/aboutus/history.html |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131209103658/http://tepv.org/aboutus/history.html |archivedate=2013-12-09 }}</ref>
