{{refimprove|date=March 2013}} {{Infobox scientist | name = Carl Barus | image = Frank Wigglesworth Clarke (and others).jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = Carl Barus (front row, 2nd from right), 1886. | birth_date = {{Birth-date|February 19, 1856}} | birth_place = [[Cincinnati]], [[United States]] | death_date = {{Death-date and age|September 20, 1935|February 19, 1856}} | death_place = [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]], [[Rhode Island]], [[United States]] | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = | residence = | citizenship = | nationality = [[Americans|American]] | fields = [[Physicist]] | workplaces = | alma_mater = [[University of Würzburg]] | doctoral_advisor = [[Friedrich Kohlrausch (physicist)|Friedrich Kohlrausch]] | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = | influences = | influenced = | awards = | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | spouse = Annie Gertrude Howes | signature = | signature_alt = | footnotes = }} '''Carl Barus''' (February 19, 1856 – September 20, 1935) was an American physicist and the maternal great-uncle of the American novelist Kurt Vonnegut.
Barus was born in [[Cincinnati]], [[United States]]. The son of German immigrants (the musician Carl Barus, Sr. and Sophia, ''nee'' Möllmann) graduated from [[Woodward High School (Cincinnati, Ohio)|Woodward High School]], together with [[William Howard Taft]], in 1874.
After studying [[mining engineering]] for two years, he moved to [[Würzburg]], [[Germany]], where he studied physics under [[Friedrich Kohlrausch (physicist)|Friedrich Kohlrausch]], and graduated ''summa cum laude'' in 1879.
Barus married Annie Gertrude Howes on January 20, 1887. They had two children, Maxwell and Deborah. In the [[United States]] in 1892, he was a member of the [[American Philosophical Society]], and the youngest of all members to [[National Academy of Sciences]].
In 1903 he was appointed as a dean of the [[Brown University]] Graduate Department, which he was controlling from his office in [[Wilson Hall (Brown University)|Wilson Hall]]. He remained the dean of the graduate school until his retirement in 1926. By that time, the department had grown large enough to become a school within the university which has been attributed to his many contributions. In 1905 he was a corresponding member of [[United Kingdom|Britain]]{{clarify|date=April 2012}} and the same year became a member of the [[First International Congress of Radiology and Electricity]] at [[Brussels]]. The same year, he became a member of the [[Physikalisch-Medizinische Sozietät]] at [[Erlangen]]. Also, the same year he became the fourth president of [[American Physical Society]], and in 1906, became a member on the advisory board of physics, at the [[Carnegie Institution]] of [[Washington (state)|Washington]] state.<ref>[http://www.brown.edu/Administration/News_Bureau/Databases/Encyclopedia/search.php?serial=B0070 Biography]</ref>
Barus died in [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]], [[Rhode Island]], [[United States]].
