{{Infobox religious biography | honorific-prefix = | name = Qiji | honorific-suffix = | native_name = 齊己 | native_name_lang = zh | image = | image_size = | caption = | religion = [[Chan Buddhism]] | school = [[Guiyang school]] |lineage = | temple = Longxing Temple | alma_mater = | other_names = Hengyue Shamen ({{zh|s=衡岳沙门|p=|labels=no}}) | dharma_names = Qiji | pen_name = | posthumous_name = | nationality = Chinese | birth_name = Hu Desheng ({{zh|s=胡德生|p=|labels=no}}) | birth_date = 863 | birth_place = [[Weishan Township, Ningxiang|Weishan Township]], [[Ningxiang]], [[Hunan]], [[China]] | death_date = {{death year and age|937|863}} | death_place = [[Jiangling County]], [[Jingzhou]], [[Hubei]], China | education = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|latitude|longitude|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} --> | spouse = | children = | parents = | title = | period = | predecessor = | successor = | rank = | teacher = [[Yangshan Huiji]] | students = | works = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | background = #FFD068 }} '''Qiji''' ({{zh|s=齐己|t=齊己|p=Qíjǐ}}; 863 - 937), also known by his [[art name]] '''Hengyue Shamen''' ({{zh|s=衡岳沙门|p=|l=Buddhist monk in Mount Hengshan|labels=no}}), was a [[Tang dynasty]] [[Chinese people|Chinese]] poet and Buddhist monk.<ref>{{cite news|author= |url=http://news.ifeng.com/a/20170817/51661040_0.shtml |script-title=zh:一字之师与好为人师 |newspaper=iFeng |date=2017-08-17 |language=zh}}</ref> Qiji has the poem more than 852, after [[Li Bai]] (701-762), [[Du Fu]] (712-770), [[Bai Juyi]] (772-846), [[Yuan Zhen]] (779-831), ranked fifth in the Tang poems.<ref>{{cite news|author= |url=http://news.163.com/17/1213/09/D5HBB20C000187VI.html |script-title=zh:成都有太多理由让远方的诗人惦念 |newspaper=163 |date=2017-12-13 |language=zh}}</ref> He was one of the big three of Tang dynasty poet and Buddhist monk ({{zh|s=诗僧|p=|labels=no}}), along with [[Guanxiu]] (832-912) and [[Jiaoran]] (730-799).
==Biography== Qiji was born Hu Desheng ({{zh|s=胡德生|p=|labels=no}}) in 863, in Zuta Village, [[Weishan Township, Ningxiang County|Weishan Township]], [[Ningxiang]], [[Hunan]], to a family of tenant farmers. At the age of 6, he learned writing while grazed cattle for the Tongdu Temple ({{zh|s=同度寺|p=|labels=no}}) on the mountain. He took refuge in the Three Jewels under the [[Yangshan Huiji]] (807-883). As Adults, he went out to study and travelled to [[Yueyang]], [[Changan]], [[Zhongnan Mountains]], [[Mount Hua]]shan, and [[Jiangxi]]. When he returned to [[Changsha]], Xu Dongye ({{zh|s=徐东野|p=|labels=no}}), a poet in the office of Hunan military governor, said: "The poems we write are not good enough. We can't compare the poems you write." ({{zh|s=我辈所作，皆拘于一途，非所谓通方之士。若齐己，才高思远，无所不通，殆难及矣。|p=|labels=no}})
In 921, Qiji went to [[Sichuan]] via [[Jingzhou]], [[Gao Jixing]] (858-929), formally Prince Wuxin of Chu, urged Qiji to stay at Longxing Temple ({{zh|s=龙兴寺|p=|labels=no}}) and appointed him as abbot. He died at the age of 76 in [[Jiangling County]], [[Jingzhou]], [[Hubei]].<ref>{{cite news|author= |url=http://fo.sina.com.cn/culture/tea/2017-06-12/doc-ifyfzhac1418830.shtml |script-title=zh:晚唐诗僧们的诗禅世界 |newspaper=sina |date=2017-06-12 |language=zh}}</ref>
