{{Italic title|reason=[[:Category:Japanese words and phrases]]}}
{{Nihongo|'''''Tō-on'''''|唐音||"[[Tang dynasty|Tang]] sound"}}, also pronounced "'''tō-in'''", are [[Japanese language|Japanese]] [[kanji]] readings imported from [[China]] by [[Zen]] monks and merchants during and after the [[Song dynasty]]. This period roughly corresponds with the mid-[[Heian period|Heian]] to [[Edo period]]s of Japan.  During the [[Muromachi period]], they were referred to as {{Nihongo|"'''sō-on'''"|宋音||"Song sound"}}.  Together, they are collectively known as {{Nihongo|"'''tōsō-on'''"|唐宋音}}.  

Scholars divide tō-on into two groups: those that are based on Zen of the Middle Ages, and those based on the [[Ōbaku]] school of Buddhism of the Middle Ages.  The latter are the readings sometimes referred to as "sō-on".

Tō-on readings are not systematic, as they were introduced piecemeal from China, often along with very specialized terminology.

Examples of words and characters using tō-on readings include: {{Nihongo|chair|椅子|isu}}, {{Nihongo|[[futon]]|蒲団}}, {{Nihongo|paper lantern|行灯|andon}}, {{Nihongo|[[Ming dynasty|Ming]]|明|min}} and {{Nihongo|[[Qing dynasty|Qing]]|清|shin}}.

